Key Match Events: MacKenzie Gore closed out his year with six scoreless innings in the Nationals' 6-3 win over the Phillies on Saturday afternoon at Nationals Park
James Wood opened up the scoring in the sixth inning with his ninth homer of the season and two runs on the board for Washington
The Nationals responded in the bottom of the eighth with a four-run rally keyed by Wood's leadoff triple
Pre-Game Insights: Manager Dave Martinez said Gore started out the season really well, then had a little lull, but finished strong with a really good month
Martinez said Gore has a 'great building block' heading into next season by studying what worked for him this month and bringing it into the spring
Post-Match Reflections: Manager Dave Martinez said Gore has a 'great building block' heading into next season by studying what worked for him this month and bringing it into the spring
Martinez said Gore should feel really good about himself, and that he should go home knowing that 'Hey, I had a really good September, and I finished up strong'
Miscellaneous Highlights: Gore dealt 91 pitches (59 strikes) over six innings, fanning nine batters and allowing just three hits and one walk
In seven starts since Aug. 23, the southpaw has posted a 1.55 ERA, allowing just seven earned runs
Gore has a 0.91 WHIP and a.181 opponents' batting average in those seven outings
Others: The Nationals secured the series win with the 6-3 victory over the Phillies
The Phillies were able to tie the game with a two-run homer by Trea Turner, but the Nationals did not miss a beat
